Being able to have an idea turn into a vision that turns into reality is what it’s all about. The vision is especially the important part. Being able to see the full potential of something or someone before it’s happen and bringing the absolute best out of it or them is the real talent.

Most never let their idea go beyond just that, the idea! They have an idea but let their fear control and blur their vision so it never goes beyond the paper it was written down on. 

I’ve always said everything we want is on the other side of fear!

So now all of our current DBC existing clients • athletes • family will be walking into the new 
10,000 sq ft.  @dbcfit 
training / recovery facility still located in the heart of the @miamidesigndistrict coming spring 2023! 

🗣️And to all of our existing clients don’t worry, we’re still staying a private boutique facility. 
No memberships, no enrollment fees, in fact, this one will be even more exclusive than ever before! 

🎥 @derick_g

𒊹︎ @rolls_royce00 
528 minutes played in 1 month 🤯
As a trainer, this is what you have to consider in your off-season. Are you putting your athlete in a position to be available at a high-level for their team ALL season long? 

𒊹︎ We need to shift our focus away from the 💨 🪞 content, and back to the metrics on their play! 

𒊹︎ Yes, in my downtime I read injury reports, minutes played, production, and everything else pertaining to watch is truly important to the players, and that’s their health and ability to be on the court! 

🗣️ Best thing you can do to qualify the trainers you follow, is follow up on those same players they’re doing off season content  with, and monitor those athletes production. That will really be an indicator if the off-season work they did truly transferred to their craft. 💡

Big shout out to the Brooklyn Nets training staff for doing an incredible job with keeping him healthy through the first part of the season!

The @dbcfit 
LEVEL 1 CERTIFICATION is headed to San Diego CA. 🌊

You can register for this course now at www.dbcfitness.com

Just as sick as some may be at seeing me do a post like this, I’m even more sick that I’m still having to do this because nobody wants to admit they’re wrong with their approach! They haven’t even announced what the injury is, but I’ll tell you right now it’s going to be a torn ACL. 

So let me explain this one more time for what feels to me like the 100 x  of me doing this on social media. 

𒊹︎ The first mechanism of an ACL tear is an anterior translation of the tibia on the femur beyond the ligament’s tolerance. This happens when an athlete rapidly decelerates from a sprint or jump with their center of mass too far forward for the momentum to be stopped. The second mechanism is torsion of the femur. 

🗣️ If we keep over training the quads of these athletes, and not understand that the turf, cleats and other things they like to say are very, very small contributing factors , if any at all, then we’re going to continue to see this happen.

𒊹︎I have nothing to gain by doing these posts, I do them, because I genuinely get sick when I see athletes suffer from what potentially could’ve been prevented. So if this upsets you to see me bring light to a very important topic, then you’re just a flat out hater or someone who doesn’t want to admit you’re possibly a part of the problem. 

📝 Put $10 million on the table and I will put together a team that will solve the non-contact ACL  injury situation in the NFL. 

Last, I’m sending big prayers to this guy that it’s not what I said it is. 🙏🏼🙏🏼🙏🏼

𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐏𝐫𝐢𝐧𝐜𝐢𝐩𝐥𝐞𝐬 𝐨𝐟 𝐚 𝐓𝐫𝐚𝐢𝐧𝐞𝐫  business seminar! 

𒊹︎I’ve been a trainer now for over 24 years and through the course of this time I kept a journal on everything i’ve accomplished, and even have failed at pertaining to the fitness industry. I want to keep people from making their early on mistakes I did when I was younger, so they can find success at a younger age. 

𒊹︎This seminar is the blue print to what every trainer, owner, influencer and anyone else in this industry needs to know.

𒊹︎There’s a lot of excitement with being in the fitness industry. But if you don’t have a plan or an understanding of what needs to happen when faced with the obstacles that this industry will present you,  you can easily find yourself in the same place making the same amount of money through your entire career. 

𒊹︎Just a few of the things that you will face if you’re not prepared are things like your gym closing, your business crashing, and something as simple as you not being able to retain clients. This happened to thousands of trainers per year because when the excitement wears off of being in the industry, this is an actual business! 

Limited seating, so secure your spot now! 
www.dbcfitness.com

Never get too comfortable! 
Familiarity breeds Disrespect

And just like that, 
My 2023, NFL off-season schedule is 
sold out. 

The art of not over extending yourself allows you to provide a much higher level of service to each individual client . 
If you can’t provide the same level of energy and focus to your last client of the day, the same way you do to your first client , don’t book it! 

𒊹︎ Now days we’re seeing more trainers stacking multiple athletes in a session just to make more money or the simple fact they don’t want to say no.  There’s nothing wrong with group training as long as each athlete has individual eyes on them and is getting the attention they pay for.

𒊹︎ As an athlete pay attention to the focus your trainer is giving you in the off-season. 
• What assessment is being done to allow them collect the proper data to design your off-season programming? 
• What are your progressions and phases through your off-season?
• What are the recovery and treatment protocols being implemented after your workouts or your days off?
This is the only opportunity you have to improve yourself both physically and mentally. 

This is why for me I don’t personally take on more than 6-7 clients in an off-season, the details matter to me.

At 46 years old this shit is A LOT more difficult to get back and maintain. 

I think it’s important to show the process, not just the final product or even worse a un-natural photo or something that’s been photoshopped! 
Last night was my once a week cheat meal, no joke. 
I had a pizza followed up with some ice cream. I didn’t prepare for this photo, I didn’t diet for a week, do a water cut or anything g that would advance my natural physical appearance.
I wanted to be as natural as possible for whoever this inspires so they understand, it’s all about balance. 

Now if you’ve followed me you know, I never do the shirtless thing, but I’m seeing this industry really miss lead a lot of the general population on what it means to be healthy. I’m ok and secure enough with putting myself out there, especially when I’m not in the most optimal shape that I would like to be right now. I’ve got about 12 more pounds to cut and there’s no secret recipe to this. I promise you there’s no quick fix or magic pill with living a healthy life. It’s about understanding your personal lifestyle, and how to create a system around that.

My weeks and days consist of 
𒊹︎Lifting Weights 
𒊹︎Running Miles
𒊹︎Golf
𒊹︎Cold Plunge 
𒊹︎Sauna
𒊹︎Hot Tub
𒊹︎No Alcohol during the week.
𒊹︎7 - 8 hours of sleep per night.
𒊹︎3.5 liters of water per day.
𒊹︎ A balanced diet of food that came from the planet! This meeting, if you didn’t run, grow, crawl, swim, or fly, I don’t put it in my body. 

Don’t be fooled by someone that cheats the process , yes, you know exactly what I mean. Or even worse be inspired by someone that photoshops their picture to a point it’s not even human.
Qualify who you follow and choose to get information from, that’s the best tip I can give you ! 
HAPPY SUNDAY, and go NINERS!

The @dbcfit LEVEL 1 CERTIFICATION 
course is an introduction to the field of biomechanics. Unlike most introductory biomechanics courses our course presents the medical and scientific research of the exercises that every personal trainer should have as a foundation to assist with their everyday programming with their clients. We present the mechanics of the general human motor programs of squatting, lunging, bending, pushing, pulling, twisting, and gait. Students learn the kinematics and kinetics of each movement and how to avoid the known mechanisms of injury. There are no prerequisites to the course so everyone from personal trainers,  ATC’s , DPT’s Strength & Conditioning coaches and fitness enthusiasts i’ve gone through this course.
He’s coming for it all! @titans CB Kristian Fulton #2023 #nfl #offseason #miami #training #athlete #development #sportsperformance #dbcfitness

As a personal trainer, helping your clients achieve their goals requires more than just pushing them through hard workouts. It requires a deep understanding of how the human body actually works, and what can happen if you prescribe  the wrong stretch or coach a movement incorrectly.  Have a deep understanding of Biomechanics will teach you that it’s not just about the short term but the long-term results and what can occur later if things aren’t done correctly in the beginning.

It doesn’t matter if you’re working with athletes, fitness enthusiast, or individuals just looking to improve their overall health and well-being. The DBC level one certification turns a personal trainer into a fitness professional.

▫️ Anaerobic Athlete Development training is all discussed and practiced, to ensure working knowledge and ability. 

𒊹︎ Coaches will develop the skillset so they are able to properly visually assess their athletes / clients through detailed  movements to determine the proper regressions and progressions to each drill. 
They will also be guided through each sport and position to learn precisely what drills can have a positive and a negative affect if programmed the correct or incorrect way to the athlete. 

𒊹︎ Last coaches will be broken up into groups to work as a team with intent to design sports specific drills with specific objectives.

This isn’t a selfie, this is a post of how I show up to work and approach my craft. 
Understanding the difference between a fitness professional and the stereotypical personal trainer. A Fitness professional is somebody  who has at least 2000 hours of hands-on training experience with actual clients. Incase you’re wondering where this number came from I’ll break it down. A good trainer, in their first 2 years, perform about 30 sessions a week,  which translates to 120 hours a month x 24 months =  2880 hours. This is just scratching the surface of calling yourself a professional. I know trainers that are doing 45 to 50 sessions a week, and then doing that for over 10 years minimum. 
A fitness professional shows up everyday and gives the same amount of energy to their last client of the day that they deliver to their first client, and everything in between.  they never slack for one hour to a paying clients.
It’s somebody who takes pride in their appearance when they got to work. Hair styled, clean hat,  clean hands for men and manicured nails for women, good breath “ this one’s mandatory, you’re talking to people all day and the last shit you want some halitosis”. 
They Invest in good sneakers and other apparel every 90 days so their look is greasy. It’s no different than how a broker on Wall Street invests in new suits. They take pride in their appearance. It is somebody who shows up early, not on time and is NEVER late. 
It’s somebody that continues to educate themselves to a higher level each year.  Even when they think they know it all, they find areas they can improve on. 
It is somebody who doesn’t eat in the middle of their session, somebody who doesn’t sit down in the middle of their session, and somebody who isn’t counting the minutes or just the reps, but is  more focused on the work. 
It’s somebody that understands that for every one of your clients that is coming in for their 60 minute workout, you are the highlight to their day and it’s about them not you. it’s somebody that knows the names to everyone in their facility not just their clients, but everyone who walks in. They make eye contact and greet people with genuine care for them.

This is a perfect example of why it’s so important to make sure your athlete can perform a perfect STATIC LUNGE , and then a DYNAMIC LUNGE  before they enter or train any sports performance. 

𒊹︎This is one of my favorite drills to implement in phase 3 of my athletes off-season training after we’ve completed and have exhausted their lower body “leg day workout”. 

𒊹︎ In the past you may have heard me speak about replicating the fourth quarter and that is exactly what I’m doing here. I’m making sure my athlete can decelerate while his body has been exhausted and in a state of fatigue.  That is how the fourth quarter is going to fill to a player who’s averaging over 35 minutes a game. 

𒊹︎The objective here is to make sure that my athlete can decelerate at a rapid pace with 50 pounds pulling him into deceleration. If they’re doing it correctly, they will end in a perfect static lunge. This will equal them loading the hip with an emphasis on hamstring and glute  activity and minimal quad activity. Result saving their knees. 👉🏼Also pay attention to his big toe on both feet and the mobility he’s able to achieve. This is a detail a lot of coaches miss. 

𒊹︎For those that may have not kept up with @rolls_royce00  first half of his Brooklyn season last year, he was averaging about 528 minutes per month! 

𒊹︎There’s nothing fancy about this drill, but it’s the not so flashy stuff that equals healthy results for the athlete in the long term.

Every drill  I do is with purpose. When I design a drill I do it with the intent it will translate directly to my athletes, sport and position. 

𒊹︎The white tape in Photo 1 is to represent the Outabounds line. I had @kriss1_  do  so many reps of this drill until it was absolutely perfect and I felt his proprioception and his awareness of his body in space was where I needed it to be. 

𒊹︎I know it’s only pre-season, but to see my guy snatch a one handed interception and  stay in bounds exactly as we drilled is the reward.

Ki-Hara Resistance Stretching is a form of exercise and flexibility training that focuses on developing flexibility, strength, and mobility through resistance and dynamic stretching techniques. It was developed based on the scientific principles drawn from a variety of disciplines including yoga, pilates, martial arts, and physical therapy.
The key concept behind Ki-Hara Resistance Stretching is that muscles and connective tissues can be effectively stretched and strengthened simultaneously by applying resistance during the stretching process. This is in contrast to traditional static stretching where you hold a position for a period of time.
Key points about Ki-Hara Resistance Stretching:
1. **Dynamic Stretching with Resistance:** In Ki-Hara, the person being stretched (the “stretchee”) actively moves a limb or body part while the trainer or partner provides resistance to that movement. This resistance can be applied manually or with the help of resistance bands.
2. **Functional Movement Patterns:** Ki-Hara Resistance Stretching emphasizes functional movement patterns that are relevant to everyday activities and sports performance. This makes it more practical for improving overall body function and performance.
3. **Strength and Flexibility Combination:** Unlike many traditional approaches that treat strength training and flexibility training as separate entities, Ki-Hara aims to integrate both aspects. The resistance provided during stretching helps in developing strength within the stretched range of motion.
4. **Injury Prevention and Rehabilitation:** Ki-Hara Resistance Stretching is often used for injury prevention and rehabilitation. It can help improve joint stability, correct imbalances, and enhance overall muscle coordination.
5. **Proprioceptive Neuromuscular Facilitation (PNF) Influence:** Ki-Hara Resistance Stretching draws inspiration from PNF techniques, which involve alternating between contraction and relaxation of muscles during stretching to achieve increased flexibility.
